<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="661" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,760,1832,2079]" lastBlockId="2.[828,1437,1545,2080]" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,270,1832,1855]" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Only macropterous male known. Body slen- der, small sized; head, pronotum, scutellum and legs with notably long setae (
<figureCitation box="[374,475,1896,1919]" captionStart="Figs 1–3" captionStartId="2.[151,188,1454,1473]" captionTargetBox="[176,1436,195,1426]" captionTargetId="figure-255@2.[148,1439,186,1436]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–3. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J, habitus. 1 – dorsal view; 2 – lateral view; 3 – ventral view. Scale bar: 2.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178044" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178044/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Figs 1–3</figureCitation>
); postocular part of head ellipsoidal, somewhat swollen (
<figureCitation box="[492,557,1928,1951]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); anterior pronotal lobe with tuberculate stripes; transverse sulcus of pronotum somewhat sinuate (
<figureCitation box="[407,473,1992,2015]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); scutellar process slender and horizontal (
<figureCitation box="[332,439,2024,2047]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
); metapleural sulcus curved (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,2056,2079]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); hind coxae separated from each other by width of one coxa (
<figureCitation box="[969,1036,1545,1568]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
); ventral surfaces of fore and middle femora with a row of denticles respectively (
<figureCitation box="[1322,1422,1577,1600]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Figs 8, 9</figureCitation>
); fore and middle tibiae with fossula spongiosa occupying only apex of ventral surfaces (
<figureCitation box="[1150,1246,1641,1664]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Figs 8, 9</figureCitation>
); hemelytron distinctly surpassing tip of abdomen, length of hemelytron nearly as long as body length; hind wing also distinctly surpassing tip of abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[1128,1207,1737,1760]" captionStart="Figs 4–12" captionStartId="3.[151,188,2006,2025]" captionTargetBox="[221,1367,753,1976]" captionTargetId="figure-272@3.[194,1394,738,1995]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 4–12. Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype, J. 4 – antennal pedicel, lateralview; 5 – anterior part of body with antennae and legs removed, dorsal view; 6 – same, lateral view; 7 – same, ventral view; 8 – left fore leg, ventral view; 9 – right middle leg, ventral view; 10 – right hemelytron, dorsal view; 11 – abdomen, ventral view; 12 – same, caudal view. Scale bar: 1.50 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178046" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178046/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); male genitalia with median pygophore process hook-shaped in caudal view (
<figureCitation box="[836,918,1801,1824]" captionStart="Figs 13–21" captionStartId="4.[151,188,2004,2023]" captionTargetBox="[251,1304,794,1981]" captionTargetId="figure-295@4.[200,1383,740,1994]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–21. Male genitalia of Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype. 13 – pygophore, ventral view; 14 – same, caudal view; 15 – same, lateral view; 16 – left paremere, outer ventrolateral view; 17 – right paramere, outer ventrolateral view; 18 – phallus, dorsal view; 19 – same, ventral view; 20 – same, lateral view; 21 – same, lateral view. Scale bar: 0.50 mm (Figs 13–15), 0.40 mm (Figs 16–21)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178048" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178048/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
); parameres paddle-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1359,1801,1824]" captionStart="Figs 13–21" captionStartId="4.[151,188,2004,2023]" captionTargetBox="[251,1304,794,1981]" captionTargetId="figure-295@4.[200,1383,740,1994]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–21. Male genitalia of Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype. 13 – pygophore, ventral view; 14 – same, caudal view; 15 – same, lateral view; 16 – left paremere, outer ventrolateral view; 17 – right paramere, outer ventrolateral view; 18 – phallus, dorsal view; 19 – same, ventral view; 20 – same, lateral view; 21 – same, lateral view. Scale bar: 0.50 mm (Figs 13–15), 0.40 mm (Figs 16–21)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178048" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178048/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Figs 16, 17</figureCitation>
); basal plate bridge about 1.5 times longer than basal plate (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs 13–21" captionStartId="4.[151,188,2004,2023]" captionTargetBox="[251,1304,794,1981]" captionTargetId="figure-295@4.[200,1383,740,1994]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–21. Male genitalia of Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype. 13 – pygophore, ventral view; 14 – same, caudal view; 15 – same, lateral view; 16 – left paremere, outer ventrolateral view; 17 – right paramere, outer ventrolateral view; 18 – phallus, dorsal view; 19 – same, ventral view; 20 – same, lateral view; 21 – same, lateral view. Scale bar: 0.50 mm (Figs 13–15), 0.40 mm (Figs 16–21)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178048" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178048/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
); dorsal phallothecal sclerite broad with apex rounded (
<figureCitation box="[835,1003,1897,1920]" captionStart="Figs 13–21" captionStartId="4.[151,188,2004,2023]" captionTargetBox="[251,1304,794,1981]" captionTargetId="figure-295@4.[200,1383,740,1994]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–21. Male genitalia of Oblongiala zimbabwensis sp. nov., holotype. 13 – pygophore, ventral view; 14 – same, caudal view; 15 – same, lateral view; 16 – left paremere, outer ventrolateral view; 17 – right paramere, outer ventrolateral view; 18 – phallus, dorsal view; 19 – same, ventral view; 20 – same, lateral view; 21 – same, lateral view. Scale bar: 0.50 mm (Figs 13–15), 0.40 mm (Figs 16–21)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5178048" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5178048/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Figs 18, 20, 21</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="661" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[828,1437,1545,2080]" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,955,1929,1952]" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Etymology.</emphasis>
Thegeneric name, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Liu &amp; Chen &amp; Webb &amp; Cai" authorityYear="2020" box="[1155,1275,1929,1952]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Oblongiala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="661" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1155,1275,1929,1952]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Oblongiala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is derived from Latin 
<emphasis box="[891,989,1961,1984]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">oblongus</emphasis>
(meaning “elongated”) and 
<emphasis box="[1294,1328,1961,1984]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">ala</emphasis>
(meaning “wing”), referring to the elongated wings of this new genus. Gender feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[828,1340,2057,2080]" pageId="2" pageNumber="661" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[828,1437,1545,2080]" box="[828,1340,2057,2080]" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,974,2057,2080]" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Distribution.</emphasis>
Afrotropical Region (
<collectingCountry box="[1208,1329,2057,2080]" name="Zimbabwe" pageId="2" pageNumber="661">Zimbabwe</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
